orrect it. Fridman analyzes three groups who exercise principles from Rich Dad, Poor Dad by playing the board game Cashflow and investing in cash-generating assets with the goal of leaving the rat race of employment. Fridman shows that the global economic transformations of the last few decades have been accompanied by popular resources that transform the people trying to survive-and even thrive.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aFinance, PersonalzArgentina. 0aFinance, PersonalzUnited States. 0aNeoliberalismzArgentina. 0aNeoliberalismzUnited States. 0aSelf-help techniqueszArgentina. 0aSelf-help techniqueszUnited States. 4aArgentina. 4acalculation. 4acapitalism. 4aeconomic performativity. 4aentrepreneurship. 4aethnography. 4agovernmentality. 4aneoliberalism. 4apersonal finance. 4aself-help. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Classes & Economic Disparity.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360026340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503600263423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503600263.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles